default2. 
defaultOpportunity Costs
default 
defaultAcc
defaultessing the waste market
defaultThe Opportunity Costs of incineration have increased dramatically 
defaultfor 
defaultcouncil
defaults in the past several years and even for those whose procurement began 3-4 years ago. 
defaultMSW can now be tendered on the competitive waste market far more cheaply (even for incineration or other ‘end of pipe’ solutions) and on shorter contracts than PPP new build. Best practice in waste management is also bringing the combined collection and di
defaultsposal costs down when recyclables, including food waste, are collected separately and the waste treated ‘per stream’.  
defaultThere has been transparency in waste treatment costs for the past 6 years with the publication of WRAP’s annual Gate Fees Reports
default whic
defaulth ‘
defaultpresents a summary of gate fees for a range of waste treatment, recovery and disposal options. The indicative gate fees reported here are based on survey information from local authorities, MRF operators, compost facility operators, waste management com
defaultpanies (WMCs) and other market intelligence’.
default The opportunity costs of not accessing the waste market are therefore now very clear with all treatments apart from landfill being considerably cheaper than incineration and in the case of recycling actually pa
defaultying councils. The information in these reports allows local authorities to make better informed decisions regarding waste ma
defaultnagement options but there is little
default evidence that the council
defaults use this information.
default 
defaultOvercapacity and falling gate fees
defaultAdrian Ju
defaultdge, now MD for Waste and Bioenergy at
default&#xa0;
defaultthe UK Green Investment Bank, has warned against the risks of an oversupply of residual waste treatment capacity, ‘
defaultTo properly assess the risks associated with finding the ‘right’ sort of substitute waste at this scal
defaulte requires a detailed understanding of the local C&amp;I waste market, and this comes at a time when funders have a lowered appetite for merchant risk’
default.
default 
defaultWaste is now a commodity like any other and one for which there is increasing competition in the UK and a
defaultt a European level; due in part to overcapacity of incineration
default and increasing recycling. All incinerators in the West Midlands area have spare capacity and older incinerators like Coventry which have the historical advantage of established waste supplier
defaults are able to charge around half the price which new build incinerators charge to remain commercially viable.
defaultDEFRA in their most recent ‘
defaultForecasting 2020 Waste Arisings and Treatment Capacity’
default 
defaultsuggests that 
default‘Spare capacity in EfW plants in Northern 
defaultEurope may tempt some LAs to exploit the relatively low gate fees there through short- to medium-term contracts rather than enter into longer-term contracts for investment in new capacity in the UK’
