default6. 
defaultDEFRA must agree Variation on VfM grounds.
default 
defaultDEFRA is being investigated by the National Audit Office in relation to its Value for Money Assessments for LA waste incinerati
defaulton plants.
default A decision by DEFRA to back a scheme and offer grants of millions of pounds is usually enough to convince a council that building its own multi-million pound incinerator is a good business proposition. However DEFRA’s decisive role in assessing
default 
defaultthe long term risks of changing waste legislation and technologies, management systems and markets in relation to costs and VfM is now being examined. 
defaultIn fact DEFRA explains its promotion of incinerator projects in terms of the short term National impera
defaulttive to meet landfill reduction targets by 2020
default rather than developing sound long term environmental and economic waste solutions for Local Authorities. As we approach the closure of the ‘waste treatment capacity gap’ by 2020 those councils singled out by
default DEFRA to get incinerators are left to face disproportionate risks compared to non-incinerator councils who are free to access short term contracts for spare capacity whilst developing newer, cheaper and greener solutions, accessing the waste market and be
defaultnefitting from the sale of recyclates.
defaultThe degree to which DEFRA performs an independent scrutiny function for incinerator proposals has been questioned in Worcestershire where there is no record of communication between WCC and DEFRA on issues 
defaultto do with 
defaultVfM. In fact the P
defaultroject’s Risk Matrix lists DEFRA itself as a risk needing mitigation: ‘
defaultSenior officers to ensure early and continuous engagement with key DEFRA officials throughout process 
defaultto ensure DEFRA buy in to scheme’default. 
defaultTreasury influence
defaultThe 
defaultTreasury’s influence over the type of waste infrastructure available to LAs is via the PFI and WI grants it allows DEFRA, its provision of infrastructure guarantees and its choice of a Private Finance system which is biased towards large inflexible infrast
defaultructure on long contracts.
defaultPFI projects have been described as ‘eye-poppingly’ expensive by Hereford MP Jesse Norman and member of the Treasury Select Committee. The Treasury, in its overriding desire for infrastructure projects (which are funded ‘off-bala
defaultnce book’) to stimulate ‘growth’ has formed an ‘
defaultunholy alliance’
default with the private contractors ‘
defaultwhich all but bypasses relevant departments in its drive to get deals done’
default.
defaultFollowing the multi-billion
default 
defaultpound bail-outs of PFI hospitals in 2012 the NAO has wa
defaultrned of the cumulative impact of funding infrastructure which is paid for from budget revenue. The Public Accounts Committee when criticising the ‘spend now, pay later’ approach of the Treasury stated; ‘
defaultWe were surprised to find that the Treasury did not hdefaultave a grip on trends in some key areas of risk or plans for managing them.default’
