defaultContractual Parameters
default1. (b) 
defaultBringing the Waste Contract into compliance with current and foreseeable legislation.
defaultThe OBC risk register for W
defaultorcestershire’s
default proposed incinerato
defaultr 
defaultis typical of other incinerator OBC’s when it 
defaultstates that if ‘
defaultthe councils significantly exceed their recycling targets
default [and] 
defaultthe plant is oversized
default’, it will be ‘
defaultan additional cost to the Councils
default’. A change in ‘
defaultthe calorific value of delivered residual
default waste’
default is also
default 
defaultstated to be ‘
defaultan additional cost to the Councils’. 
default The Councils are named as the ‘risk owners’ in the Risk Matrix for changes in legislation or guidance either at European, National or Regional/local level. 
defaultThese are very great risks for 
defaultc
defaultouncils who will be unable to respond to the rapidly changing waste world
default without paying the private partner
default to provide extra new waste services or infrastructure. This process has already been witnessed by WCC where Mercia’s 15 year old waste contract ha
defaults needed 56 variations costing £49 million in order to bring services in line with new environmental policy and legislation. 
defaultThe EU Waste Directive is proposing to ban the incineration of all recyclable and organic material by 2020
default 
defaultwhich 
defaultcould clearly resu
defaultlt in incinerators becoming economically unviable. 
defaultIt 
defaultappears 
defaultthat the recommendations of the 
defaultTreasury Select Committee
default that ‘
defaultPFI is only likely to be suitable where the risks associated with future demand and usage of the asset can be efficiently transfe
defaultrred to the private sector’ 
defaulthave not been followed.
defaultDEFRA, who are tasked with applying the trajectory of waste policy in relation to incinerator sizing for waste contracts, forecasts recycling rates peaking at around 50% in 2020 and remaining static for t
defaulthe next 25 years. This appears to contradict both reality and its own Waste Strategy for moving towards a Zero Waste Society. Wales is already exceeding 50% nationally and like Scotland aims for 70-75% within a few years. The Audit Commission’s document ‘W
defaultell Disposed’ states ‘
defaultaround 70% of household waste is readily recyclable’ 
defaultwhich is confirmed by the top performing councils in England who are now achieving around 70%. 
defaultIncinerator business cases are being passed by DEFRA without sensitivity analysis for
default 60 and 70 % recycling being carried out.
default 
defaultDespite being a prime example of infrastructure involving long-term commercial risk incinerator projects have not had either the academic research or governmental monitoring and oversight which other large privatel
defaulty funded LA infrastructure have received. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn contrast to the conservative predictions of DEFRA, and those parts of the waste industry wishing to secure incinerator contracts, the waste industry as a whole is gearing up to move its investment to the newer
default forms of waste treatment and sees ‘
defaultthe waste market is evolving into one with shorter-term local authority contracts and contracts based on specific waste streams across municipal and commercial sectors.’ 
defaultInvestment will come from ‘
defaultCorporate investors…, t
defaulthe GIB…, overseas buyers attracted to both the scale of investment and pace of change in the market and Private equity attracted to the growth potential in areas such as recycling.’
